</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B1F02CFD75FB36E4B5FB86B79B58976" pageId="106" pageNumber="107">
TURKEY, Constantinople, 
<emphasis id="2C0063C8A14722A5CE73632910A91DE9" italics="true" pageId="106" pageNumber="107">G. V. Aznavour</emphasis>
(neotype BM!, designated by Staples in 
<bibRefCitation id="12525B78B0B371ED12FDDEF38FF6B854" author="Staples, GW" journalOrPublisher="Taxon" pageId="212" pageNumber="213" pagination="1019 - 1024" publicationUrl="10.2307/25065700" refId="B348" refString="Staples, GW, Jarvis, C, 2006. Typification of Linnaean plant names in Convolvulaceae. Taxon 55: 1019 - 1024, DOI: 10.2307/25065700" title="Typification of Linnaean plant names in Convolvulaceae." url="10.2307/25065700" volume="55" year="2006">Staples and Jarvis 2006</bibRefCitation>
: 1021); isoneotypes B, E!, P!).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="BAA6865AE2EBA8E8704DA1C4D84C153B" pageId="106" pageNumber="107" type="description">
<paragraph id="22A8BAE0F149035BAFAD747D30E9F6E4" pageId="106" pageNumber="107">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7C3F019EAE8E5BDB11084C6D584E8386" pageId="106" pageNumber="107">
Perennial branched undershrub with woody rootstock and lower branches, the whole plant shortly tomentose; stems very stout, 3-5 mm thick. Leaves petiolate, coriaceous, 2-5 
<normalizedToken id="FC919FC29E1B6BF8A07B93747C0EB029" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1-3.5 cm, elliptic, oblong-elliptic or obovate, apex obtuse to rounded, margin entire, base broadly cuneate to rounded, slightly asymmetric; petioles 0-6 cm. Flowers solitary, axillary, pedunculate, usually arising from the middle part of the stem; peduncles 0.8-3.3 cm; bracteoles 3-5 
<normalizedToken id="9A16B56FC7DD48E8053067E1BCFD2102" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
1-3 mm, ovate to oblong-elliptic, acute; pedicels 5-7 mm; sepals 12-15 
<normalizedToken id="6D4BF45E9824760BE315C23DF22428DB" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
7-9 mm, ovate, obtuse or acute; corolla 3-4.5 cm, white, unlobed, undulate, midpetaline bands pilose; filaments glandular below; ovary very narrow, thinly pilose at apex; style divided c. 18 mm above base; stigmas 2 mm, narrowly elliptic. Capsule glabrous, seeds tuberculate. [
<bibRefCitation id="1D8CBAA55015F2CC38E6441EC5156FB6" author="Sa'ad, F" journalOrPublisher="Bronder Offset, Rotterdam" pageId="210" pageNumber="211" pagination="1 - 287" refId="B314" refString="Sa'ad, F, 1967. The Convolvulus species of the Canary Isles, the Mediterranean region, and the Near and Middle East. Mededelingen van het Botanisch Museum en Herbarium van de Rijksuniversite Utrecht. Bronder Offset, Rotterdam: 1 - 287" title="The Convolvulus species of the Canary Isles, the Mediterranean region, and the Near and Middle East. Mededelingen van het Botanisch Museum en Herbarium van de Rijksuniversite Utrecht" year="1967">
<normalizedToken id="F38638A34FCBE501366661F56E54953F" originalValue="Sa’ad">Sa'ad</normalizedToken>
1967
</bibRefCitation>
: 163; 
<bibRefCitation id="BCCDB914580D6ACCD3D8C31E7E5505CA" author="Nowroozi, M" journalOrPublisher="Ministry of Jihad-e-Agriculture, Iran" pageId="207" pageNumber="208" pagination="1 - 110" refId="B244" refString="Nowroozi, M, 2002. Flora of Iran 40: Convolvulaceae. Ministry of Jihad-e-Agriculture, Iran: 1 - 110" title="Flora of Iran 40: Convolvulaceae" year="2002">Nowrooze 2002</bibRefCitation>
: 103 (map); 
<bibRefCitation id="3341752F5C4B1CE36B9E6FA9BD2BB824" author="Grigoriev, C" journalOrPublisher="USSR Scientific Academy, Moscow and Leningrad" pageId="203" pageNumber="204" pagination="1 - 37" refId="B138" refString="Grigoriev, C, 1953. Flora USSR volume 19: Tubiflorae. USSR Scientific Academy, Moscow and Leningrad: 1 - 37" title="Flora USSR volume 19: Tubiflorae" year="1953">Grigoriev 1953</bibRefCitation>
: 11 (plate)]
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="76987481136B181A629F38535B5BF1A2" pageId="106" pageNumber="107" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="3483AED6C84A39474A7C9F35ED1544B3" pageId="106" pageNumber="107">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="80750615921DC935D2DC73284654EEC4" pageId="106" pageNumber="107">
Coasts of the Black Sea: Georgia (
<emphasis id="4FACDE43759BF8735DBC4F111670E2FC" italics="true" pageId="106" pageNumber="107">Cosson</emphasis>
8 in Hohenacker), Turkey (
<emphasis id="140B8240E20A6177DED68A6036BD3494" italics="true" pageId="106" pageNumber="107">
Olivier &amp; 
<normalizedToken id="2EBBC069138B7747372A5FE950312C45" originalValue="Brugière">Brugiere</normalizedToken>
</emphasis>
s.n., 
<emphasis id="A25F48FFD32572DA0BECC125436EC629" italics="true" pageId="106" pageNumber="107">Uslu</emphasis>
2141), Bulgaria (
<emphasis id="B51E5E443F2844D60C17BD6D180698D5" italics="true" pageId="106" pageNumber="107">Bosseva et al</emphasis>
. 88), Romania (
<emphasis id="C8B3A93D5E79E65DC45A56D3D310F30B" italics="true" pageId="106" pageNumber="107">Grintescu</emphasis>
1094b) and Caspian Sea: Russia [Daghestan] (
<emphasis id="C2E38A70C8BC9F5D981ED06216E9DC5E" italics="true" pageId="106" pageNumber="107">Becker</emphasis>
1876), Azerbaijan (
<emphasis id="D2E811D35946FF15F455584557D218C3" italics="true" pageId="106" pageNumber="107">Lewandowsky</emphasis>
519, 
<emphasis id="3C4DDD174B42CE8844638FDB29A0E2F3" italics="true" pageId="106" pageNumber="107">Kerimov</emphasis>
32), Iran (
<emphasis id="4A9A056803F4287500256E2EA9AE22FC" italics="true" pageId="106" pageNumber="107">Aucher-Eloy</emphasis>
4940), Turkmenistan (
<emphasis id="806A63378FF609685A9161DE53FDC327" italics="true" pageId="106" pageNumber="107">Dubiansky</emphasis>
s.n. [14/7/1932]). Coastal sand dunes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="307BF5D4EE5BA3B9B8D65304CC8D12BC" pageId="106" pageNumber="107" type="notes">
